(1739, 281, 'the_journey_so_far_image', '157'),
(1740, 281, '_the_journey_so_far_image', 'field_637c73735ede7'),
(1741, 281, 'the_journey_so_far_paragraph_1', '<strong>Pictura Bio’s groundbreaking diagnostic platform</strong> was born out of a unique combination of medical and technical expertise in <strong>virology, biophysics</strong> and <strong>microscopy</strong> from the company’s co-founders, <span>Dr Nicole Robb</span> and <span>Nicolas Shiaelis</span>.'),
(1742, 281, '_the_journey_so_far_paragraph_1', 'field_637c73b65ede8'),
(1743, 281, 'the_journey_so_far_paragraph_2', 'Nicole, an infectious disease specialist from the University of Warwick with more than 15 years’ experience studying viruses, and her team discovered a new way of universally labelling pathogens so they could be studied in the lab. Nicolas, a PhD student in Biophysics at Oxford University with experience in computer vision and machine learning, combined Nicole’s newly discovered labelling method with a novel pre-processing algorithm and machine learning to detect and identify individual pathogens.\r\n\r\nTogether, they realised that combining these tools and their knowledge had the potential to create a completely new way of detecting pathogens.\r\n\r\nOne of the first people to spot the revolutionary potential of this new technology was Alex Batchelor, now the CEO of Pictura Bio. Alex has decades of experience in the rapid diagnostics space and has previously led an Oxford University spin-out from its earliest days through to a successful split into two new companies.'),
(1744, 281, '_the_journey_so_far_paragraph_2', 'field_637c73ef5ede9'),
(1745, 281, 'our_goals_title', 'Our goal today:'),
(1746, 281, '_our_goals_title', 'field_637c7d1303652'),
(1747, 281, 'our_goals_paragraph_1', 'The Pictura Bio team is initially focusing on packaging the <span>PIC-ID technology</span> into a simple desktop ‘lab in a box’, around the size of a domestic microwave, comprising a single-purpose high-powered fluorescence microscope and image capture and processing technology.'),
(1748, 281, '_our_goals_paragraph_1', 'field_637c7d2803653'),
(1749, 281, 'our_goals_paragraph_2', '<p>\r\nOnce the box is ready, Pictura Bio’s goal is to get it straight into the hands of the people on the healthcare frontline who need it most.\r\n\r\nFollowing clinical validation and regulatory approval, PIC-ID will be deployable anywhere a laboratory-grade test is needed, taking testing from the lab out into the community.\r\n</p>'),
(1750, 281, '_our_goals_paragraph_2', 'field_637c7d6403654'),
(1751, 281, 'our_goals_paragraph_3', 'Imagine a PIC-ID box in your local high street pharmacy or GP surgery, able to reveal in seconds whether your nasty cough is just a cold or something more serious. Or at the fingertips of a busy hospital doctor who needs an answer right now to determine how best to treat her critically ill patient.'),
(1752, 281, '_our_goals_paragraph_3', 'field_637c7d6f03655'),
(1753, 281, 'our_goals_team_indicator', 'You can read more about our team below'),
(1754, 281, '_our_goals_team_indicator', 'field_637c7d8103656'),
(1755, 281, 'investment_title', 'Investment:'),
(1756, 281, '_investment_title', 'field_637c7f20b08eb'),
(1757, 281, 'investment_paragraph_1', 'Pictura Bio holds <span>IP rights</span> over the <span>two key components of the PIC-ID platform</span> – the universal label and the deep learning algorithm – and has secured £2.6 million in pre-seed funding from deep tech investors IQ Capital Partners, Ahren Innovation Capital and ScienceCreates Ventures.'),
(1758, 281, '_investment_paragraph_1', 'field_637c7e5fe1b1a'),
(1759, 281, 'investment_paragraph_2', 'While there is nothing similar to PIC-ID on the market, other companies in the computer vision and machine-learning medical space – such as digital pathology platforms that can analyse images of tumour tissue or AI-assisted analysis of X-ray scans – demonstrate a clear and viable route to regulatory approval and reimbursement for Pictura Bio’s technology.\r\n \r\nGiven the global scale of infectious disease and the ever-present threat of emerging diseases, there’s a huge potential market to be tapped.\r\n \r\nThe global infectious disease diagnostic market was valued at $27.8 billion in 2021, and is expected to grow to $41.2 billion by 2028. Add in future applications in other diseases, and the opportunities are vast.'),
(1760, 281, '_investment_paragraph_2', 'field_637c7e90e1b1b'),
(1761, 281, 'investment_paragraph_3', 'With no direct competition in the image-based diagnostics field, Pictura Bio is uniquely placed as the global front-runner in this space.'),
(1762, 281, '_investment_paragraph_3', 'field_637c7e9de1b1c'),
